04528nam a22006375i 9780520384910DE-B159720230529094047.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230529t20232023cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97805203849107 a10.1525/97805203849102doi  a(DE-B1597)642426  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 4aHQ1150b.M345 2023 7aSOC0730002bisacsh04a305.420973223/eng/202212221 aMajic, Samantha, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aLights, Camera, Feminism? :bCelebrities and Anti-trafficking Politics /cSamantha Majic. 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[2023] 4c©2023  a1 online resource (312 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tAcknowledgments -- tList of Acronyms -- tIntroduction: Celebrities, Feminism, and Human Trafficking -- t1 • Theory and Methods: Celebrity Feminism, Performance, and Political Representation -- t2 • Performing Feminism: Celebrities’ Anti-trafficking Activism, 2000–2016 -- t3 • White Saviors and Activist Mothers: Ashley Judd, Jada Pinkett Smith, and the Sex Trafficking of Women and Girls -- t4 • Latin Lovers and Tech Guys: Ricky Martin, Ashton Kutcher, and Variations of Male Celebrity Feminism -- t5 • Anti-trafficking Ambassadors: Julia Ormond, Mira Sorvino, and the UNODC -- tConclusion: Celebrity, Power, and Political Accountability -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aCelebrities in the United States have drawn significant attention and resources to the complex issue of human trafficking—a subject of feminist concern—and they are often criticized for promoting sensationalized and simplistic understandings of the issue. In this comprehensive analysis of celebrities’ anti-trafficking activism, however, Samantha Majic finds that this phenomenon is more nuanced: even as some celebrities promote regressive issue narratives and carceral solutions, others use their platforms to elevate more diverse representations of human trafficking and feminist analyses of gender inequality. Lights, Camera, Feminism? thus argues that we should understand celebrities as multilevel political actors whose activism is shaped and mediated by a range of personal and contextual factors, with implications for feminist and democratic politics more broadly.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aCelebritiesxPolitical activityzUnited States. 0aEqualityzUnited States. 0aFeminismxPolitical aspectszUnited States. 0aHuman traffickingzUnited StatesxPrevention. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Human Trafficking.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023 Englishz978311131929208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023z9783111318912oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Sociology 2023 Englishz978311131926108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Sociology 2023z9783111318806oZDB-23-DSL08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2023z978311079134140uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/9780520384910?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520384910423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520384910/original  a978-3-11-079134-1  University of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2023b2023  a978-3-11-131926-1  EBOOK PACKAGE Sociology 2023 Englishb2023  a978-3-11-131929-2  EBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023 Englishb2023  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-DGGb2023  aZDB-23-DSLb2023  aZDB-23-UCY